<h1>From Edmond Atkin</h1>

<div class="docbody">
<div class="opener">
<table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">Sir</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">Winchester 20 July 1757</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
</div>
<p>When the 10 Indians were taken into Custody yesterday was Sennight,<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-04-02-0212-fn-0001" id="GEWN-02-04-02-0212-fn-0001-ptr">1</a> you may remember I expressed my Desire, that they might be treated in point of Necessaries rather better than before, because it was pretended that two of them were CherokeesOn Saturday Morning being informed, that the Prisoners made great Complaint for want of fresh Meat, and that Some of them had contracted Fluxes by a Diet they had not been used to, I took the Liberty to Send for the Provincial Commissarys Clerk, &amp; made an Inquiry from him about it. He told me, it was true they had before that time had no fresh Meat; that the Commissary was disappointed of Some Cattle he expected the Evening before, which would certainly be here that night; and the Prisoners should have fresh Meat the next Morning. I remember you told me Soon after my first coming here, that the Indians in general Might have fresh Meat (of which they were desirous) as well as Salt, it being all one to the Publick.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-04-02-0212-fn-0002" id="GEWN-02-04-02-0212-fn-0002-ptr">2</a> On Sunday afternoon Dr Craick, who had been called in to the Relief of the Sick Prisoners, told me, that they had had no fresh Meat; and that he thought it was absolutely necessary for them, being in a bad Condition.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-04-02-0212-fn-0003" id="GEWN-02-04-02-0212-fn-0003-ptr">3</a> And I desired, that he would require it.</p>
<p>This forenoon the Jailer was with me expressing his Concern for the Resentment the Prisoners shewed for their Treatment, having had only about 4 librae of fresh Beef brought &amp; dressed by the Cook (one of your Soldiers) on Monday, and yesterday 4 or 5 librae (besides Bacon), among them all. Whereupon I Sent again for the Commissarys Clerk, who told me, that he delivered to the Cook for those Prisoners 35 librae of fresh Beef on Monday, &amp; 18 librae yesterday besides the remainder of the Allowance
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-02-04-02-pb-0322">[322]</span>
in Bacon; And that he had not any fresh Meat to give them this day, but proposed to Send Bacon; which the Jailer Said, most of the Prisoners Stomachs Nauseate so much, that they cannot Swallow it.</p>
<p>This gives me no Small Concern; because if, when the Cherokee Chiefs now out at War come to Town, it should appear that two of the Prisoners are Cherokees for whom they shall think fit to interest themselves; and it should unluckily prove to be the Case of either of those very Indians to die in the Prison, I cannot answer what will be the Consequence to his Majestys Service.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-04-02-0212-fn-0004" id="GEWN-02-04-02-0212-fn-0004-ptr">4</a> My own Opinion is, that while any fresh Meat is to be had, those Prisoners ought not to go without it, whoever else do. I would rather go without any myself, for one.</p>
<p>Had I any Authority over the Persons concerned in this Affair, I would certainly punish Some Body or other. As it is, I lay the Matter before you, not in the least doubting that you will inquire further into it, &amp; do whatever shall appear to you to be right. I am Sir Your most Obedt Servt</p>
<div class="closer">
<p class="signed">Edmd Atkin</p>
</div>
<div class="postscript">
<p>P.S. The Beer Sent to the Prisoners was so bad, that they could not drink it. And one of my Servants who tasted it, said it was not fit to drink.</p>
<p>I think it very odd, that the getting fresh Provision should be left till the Indians are waiting to eat it.</p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="docback">
<div class="note-source" id="GEWN-02-04-02-0212-sn">

   <p>
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Autograph Letter Signed: a letter in the handwriting of, and signed by, the author ]">ALS</abbr>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>.
</p>

</div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-04-02-0212-fn-0001-ptr" id="GEWN-02-04-02-0212-fn-0001">1</a>

   <p>For GWs account of Atkins imprisoning these Indians, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-04-02-0200" class="document">GW to John Stanwix, 15 July 1757</a>. For Atkins account, see the notes to that letter and <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-04-02-0207&amp;expandNote=GEWN-02-04-02-0207-fn-0001#GEWN-02-04-02-0207-fn-0001" class="document">Stanwix to GW, 18 July, n.1.</a></p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-04-02-0212-fn-0002-ptr" id="GEWN-02-04-02-0212-fn-0002">2</a>

   <p>Despite his long absence, Dr. Thomas Walker still held the title of commissary. It is not known either to whom Atkin was referring here as commissary or who the clerk was.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-04-02-0212-fn-0003-ptr" id="GEWN-02-04-02-0212-fn-0003">3</a>

   <p>Dr. James Craik (c.17301814) had been in the Virginia Regiment since the fall of 1755. Earlier he served as surgeon with the rank of ensign in GWs detachment during the Fort Necessity campaign in 1754.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-04-02-0212-fn-0004-ptr" id="GEWN-02-04-02-0212-fn-0004">4</a>

   <p>In his report to Stanwix on 15 July (see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-04-02-0212&amp;expandNote=GEWN-02-04-02-0212-fn-0001#GEWN-02-04-02-0212-fn-0001" class="document">note 1</a>) GW told of Atkins sending to the South Branch for the ailing Ostenaco and referred to the anticipated return of the Indians who had gone to Fort Duquesne from Fort Cumberland on 9 July.</p>

</div>
</div>
